Task 1: Set Up Basic Firewall Rules with UFW
Subtask 1.1: Install and Check UFW Status
First, let's verify that UFW is installed and check its current status.

Step 1: Check if UFW is installed on your system:

sudo ufw --version
Step 2: If UFW is not installed, install it using the package manager:

sudo apt update
sudo apt install ufw -y
Step 3: Check the current status of UFW:

sudo ufw status
You should see output indicating that UFW is inactive (disabled by default).

Step 4: View the current UFW rules in verbose mode:

sudo ufw status verbose
Subtask 1.2: Enable UFW and Configure Default Policies
Step 1: Before enabling UFW, set up default policies to ensure you don't lock yourself out:

sudo ufw default deny incoming
sudo ufw default allow outgoing
Step 2: Allow SSH connections to prevent being locked out of your system:

sudo ufw allow ssh
Step 3: Enable UFW firewall:

sudo ufw enable
Type y when prompted to proceed with the operation.

Step 4: Verify that UFW is now active:

sudo ufw status
You should see that UFW is active with SSH allowed.

Subtask 1.3: Configure Basic Service Rules
Step 1: Allow HTTP traffic (port 80):

sudo ufw allow http
Step 2: Allow HTTPS traffic (port 443):

sudo ufw allow https
Step 3: Allow FTP traffic (port 21):

sudo ufw allow ftp
Step 4: View all current rules:

sudo ufw status numbered
Step 5: Allow a specific port (example: port 8080):

sudo ufw allow 8080
Step 6: Allow a port with specific protocol:

sudo ufw allow 3306/tcp
Subtask 1.4: Test Basic Deny Rules
Step 1: Deny access to a specific port (example: port 23 for Telnet):

sudo ufw deny 23
Step 2: Deny access to a specific service:

sudo ufw deny smtp
Step 3: Check the updated rules:

sudo ufw status verbose
Task 2: Create Custom Firewall Policies
Subtask 2.1: IP Address-Based Rules
Step 1: Allow connections from a specific IP address:

sudo ufw allow from 192.168.1.100
Step 2: Allow connections from a specific IP address to a specific port:

sudo ufw allow from 192.168.1.100 to any port 22
Step 3: Allow connections from a subnet:

sudo ufw allow from 192.168.1.0/24
Step 4: Deny connections from a specific IP address:

sudo ufw deny from 203.0.113.100
Step 5: Allow connections from a specific IP to a specific service:

sudo ufw allow from 10.0.0.50 to any port 80
Subtask 2.2: Port Range Rules
Step 1: Allow a range of ports:

sudo ufw allow 6000:6010/tcp
Step 2: Allow UDP traffic on a port range:

sudo ufw allow 60000:61000/udp
Step 3: Deny a range of ports:

sudo ufw deny 135:139/tcp
Subtask 2.3: Interface-Specific Rules
Step 1: Check available network interfaces:

ip addr show
Step 2: Allow traffic on a specific interface (replace eth0 with your interface name):

sudo ufw allow in on eth0 to any port 80
Step 3: Allow traffic from a specific interface to a specific destination:

sudo ufw allow in on lo to any port 3306
Subtask 2.4: Application-Specific Rules
Step 1: List available application profiles:

sudo ufw app list
Step 2: Get information about a specific application profile:

sudo ufw app info 'Apache Full'
Step 3: Allow an application profile:

sudo ufw allow 'Apache Full'
Step 4: Create a custom application profile. First, create a profile file:

sudo nano /etc/ufw/applications.d/myapp
Add the following content:

[MyWebApp]
title=My Custom Web Application
description=Custom web application on port 8080
ports=8080/tcp
Step 5: Reload UFW application profiles:

sudo ufw app update MyWebApp
Step 6: Allow the custom application:

sudo ufw allow MyWebApp
Task 3: Use UFW for Logging and Troubleshooting
Subtask 3.1: Enable and Configure UFW Logging
Step 1: Enable UFW logging:

sudo ufw logging on
Step 2: Set logging level to medium for more detailed logs:

sudo ufw logging medium
Step 3: Check available logging levels:

sudo ufw logging --help
Step 4: Set logging to high level for maximum detail:

sudo ufw logging high
Subtask 3.2: View and Analyze UFW Logs
Step 1: View UFW logs using journalctl:

sudo journalctl -u ufw
Step 2: View recent UFW log entries:

sudo journalctl -u ufw -n 20
Step 3: Follow UFW logs in real-time:

sudo journalctl -u ufw -f
Step 4: View UFW logs from system log files:

sudo grep UFW /var/log/syslog
Step 5: View only blocked connections:

sudo grep "UFW BLOCK" /var/log/syslog
Subtask 3.3: Generate Test Traffic for Log Analysis
Step 1: Open a second terminal window and attempt to connect to a blocked port:

telnet localhost 23
Step 2: In your main terminal, check the logs for the blocked connection:

sudo grep "UFW BLOCK" /var/log/syslog | tail -5
Step 3: Test an allowed connection:

curl -I http://localhost
Step 4: Check logs for allowed connections:

sudo grep "UFW ALLOW" /var/log/syslog | tail -5
Subtask 3.4: UFW Status and Rule Management
Step 1: Display detailed UFW status:

sudo ufw status verbose
Step 2: Show numbered rules for easy management:

sudo ufw status numbered
Step 3: Delete a specific rule by number (replace X with actual rule number):

sudo ufw delete 5
Step 4: Delete a rule by specification:

sudo ufw delete allow 8080
Step 5: Insert a rule at a specific position:

sudo ufw insert 1 allow from 192.168.1.50
Subtask 3.5: Advanced Troubleshooting Commands
Step 1: Check UFW configuration files:

sudo cat /etc/ufw/ufw.conf
Step 2: View UFW rules in raw iptables format:

sudo ufw show raw
Step 3: Display UFW listening report:

sudo ufw show listening
Step 4: Show UFW added rules:

sudo ufw show added
Step 5: Reset UFW to default settings (use with caution):

sudo ufw --force reset
Subtask 3.6: Create a Comprehensive Firewall Policy Script
Create a script to implement a complete firewall policy:

Step 1: Create a new script file:

nano ~/firewall_setup.sh
Step 2: Add the following content to the script:

#!/bin/bash

# UFW Firewall Configuration Script
echo "Starting UFW Firewall Configuration..."

# Reset UFW to clean state
sudo ufw --force reset

# Set default policies
sudo ufw default deny incoming
sudo ufw default allow outgoing

# Allow essential services
sudo ufw allow ssh
sudo ufw allow http
sudo ufw allow https

# Allow specific applications
sudo ufw allow 'Apache Full'

# Allow database access from local network only
sudo ufw allow from 192.168.1.0/24 to any port 3306

# Allow custom application port
sudo ufw allow 8080/tcp

# Deny dangerous services
sudo ufw deny telnet
sudo ufw deny ftp

# Allow ping (ICMP)
sudo ufw allow in on any to any port 22
sudo ufw allow out on any from any to any port 22

# Enable logging
sudo ufw logging medium

# Enable UFW
sudo ufw enable

# Display final status
echo "UFW Configuration Complete!"
sudo ufw status verbose

echo "Firewall setup completed successfully!"
Step 3: Make the script executable:

chmod +x ~/firewall_setup.sh
Step 4: Run the script:

./firewall_setup.sh
Subtask 3.7: Monitor and Analyze Firewall Performance
Step 1: Create a log monitoring script:

nano ~/ufw_monitor.sh
Step 2: Add the following content:

#!/bin/bash

echo "UFW Firewall Monitoring Report"
echo "=============================="
echo

echo "Current UFW Status:"
sudo ufw status verbose
echo

echo "Recent Blocked Connections (Last 10):"
sudo grep "UFW BLOCK" /var/log/syslog | tail -10
echo

echo "Recent Allowed Connections (Last 5):"
sudo grep "UFW ALLOW" /var/log/syslog | tail -5
echo

echo "Top Blocked IP Addresses:"
sudo grep "UFW BLOCK" /var/log/syslog | awk '{print $13}' | sort | uniq -c | sort -nr | head -5
echo

echo "Monitoring complete!"
Step 3: Make the monitoring script executable:

chmod +x ~/ufw_monitor.sh
Step 4: Run the monitoring script:

./ufw_monitor.sh
Troubleshooting Tips
Common Issues and Solutions
Issue 1: Locked out of SSH after enabling UFW

Solution: If you have physical access, disable UFW with sudo ufw disable and reconfigure
Issue 2: Rules not working as expected

Solution: Check rule order with sudo ufw status numbered - rules are processed in order
Issue 3: Application profiles not found

Solution: Update application database with sudo ufw app update --add-new
Issue 4: Logs not showing expected entries

Solution: Increase logging level with sudo ufw logging high
Issue 5: Cannot delete rules

Solution: Use numbered deletion sudo ufw delete [number] or exact rule specification
Best Practices
Always allow SSH before enabling UFW
Test rules thoroughly before implementing in production
Use specific IP ranges instead of allowing all traffic when possible
Regularly review and audit firewall rules
Monitor logs for suspicious activity
Keep UFW rules organized and well-documented
Use application profiles when available
Implement defense in depth with multiple security layers
